The article is a presidential proclamation by Barack Obama declaring June 2010 as Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, and Transgender (LGBT) Pride Month. The proclamation highlights the contributions of LGBT Americans to society and emphasizes the need for equal rights and an end to prejudice and injustice. It mentions various actions taken by the Obama Administration to advance LGBT rights, such as signing the Matthew Shepard and James Byrd, Jr., Hate Crimes Prevention Act and directing hospitals to provide compassionate care to LGBT patients. The proclamation also calls for further progress, including repealing the Defense of Marriage Act, protecting adoption rights, ending employment discrimination, creating safer schools, and ending the "Don't Ask, Don't Tell" policy in the military. It concludes by urging all Americans to fight prejudice and discrimination in their own lives.